	abstract = {In complex water environments, unmanned ships face various constraints such as sailing speed, heading, obstacles, weather conditions, and water currents. Achieving efficient path planning and effectively avoiding both static and dynamic obstacles under these complex conditions to ensure the safety and stability of unmanned ship navigation is a significant technical challenge. This paper proposes a path planning and intelligent obstacle avoidance strategy for unmanned ships, combining an improved A∗ algorithm and the Dynamic Window Approach (DWA), aimed at addressing path planning and dynamic obstacle avoidance in complex water environments. The algorithm dynamically adjusts heading, speed, and acceleration through real-time perception of environmental changes (such as dynamic obstacles), achieving efficient path planning. Additionally, it optimizes path smoothing techniques by combining A∗ with DWA to reduce heading changes, improving navigation stability and energy efficiency. The results show that the path planning time was reduced from 152.31 seconds to 140.93 seconds, and the path length was shortened from 27.31 meters to 24.34 meters, achieving an optimization of approximately 7.5% and 11%, respectively. The proposed method not only effectively addresses navigation challenges under complex constraints but also significantly enhances the autonomous navigation capability of unmanned ships in complex environments. This research provides innovative solutions for autonomous systems, robotic path planning, and intelligent control systems, laying a foundation for the future application of unmanned ships in dynamic marine environments. © 2025 IEEE.},
